                                                                                                               Demand for disaster shield
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                               
	Bhubaneswar, March 18: Members of the Orissa Assembly today urged the government to take measures to combat natural disasters pointing out to the states vulnerability along the 480km coastline.        
	Orissa is located on the countrys east-coast and has a unique geo-climate that makes it particularly vulnerable to tsunamis, cyclones and floods, said the Opposition legislators. They came down heavily on the government for its casual approach towards natural calamities.         
	The government seems to think that its job is over after writing letters to the Centre seeking funds, said NCP leader Arun Dey.         
	Dey represents Balasore, a coastal town that often face many disasters. He alleged that the government had not taken tangible measures  mangrove plantation or strengthening saline embankments  to protect his area.         
	Responding to the questions, disaster management minister Manmohan Samal assured that the government had taken a number of measures to mitigate impacts of disasters.         
	Listing the measures the minister said tsunami mitigation plans had been prepared for 328 tsunami-prone villages.         
	A national workshop had been organised to study reasons behind intense heat waves. It was attended by experts from Indian meteorology department and IIT, Delhi, and Kharagpur, he said.         
	He added that the government had submitted a detailed Rs 609.40-crore proposal to the Centre under the National Cyclone Risk Mitigation Project.                                                                                                                                                                            
